<div class=" clearFloats bigBox"><div class="h2Container gradientHeaderContainer"><h2 class="brownBackground">Reader Q&amp;A</h2></div><div class="bigBoxBody"><div class="bigBoxContent containerWithHeaderContent"><div class='communityQASignedOutMessage mediumText'>
To ask other readers questions about
<a class="bookLink" href="/book/show/39063.Titus_Groan">Titus Groan</a>,
<a class="actionLink" rel="nofollow" href="/user/new">please sign up</a>.
</div>

<div class='elementListBrownSeparator'></div>
<div class='communityQuestionSubTitle'>
Popular Answered Questions
</div>
<div id='communityQuestionsWithAnswers'>
<div class='communityQuestionAndAnswer'>
<div class='communityQuestion'>
<div class='questionText'>
<a href="/questions/780196-is-this-one-of-those-books-that-is">Is this one of those books that is technically good but so tongue in cheek and academic that it is divorced from an organic relation to the folk sensitivities of people, as opposed to say... the work of Tolkien with its huge epic, religious, mystic and traditional representations in earnest?

Is this also the sort of book people criticize negatively based on their own ineptitude (e.g. &quot;hard to read&quot;)?</a>
</div>
<div class='communityQAFooter questionFooter'>
<ul class='questionFooterActions'>
<li class='footerItem like'>
<span class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_community_question_780196'><a id="like_count_community_question_780196" rel="nofollow" href="/rating/voters/780196?resource_type=CommunityQuestion"><span class="likesCount">4 likes</span></a>&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;<a rel="nofollow" class="jsLike like_it" href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F39063.Titus_Groan">like</a></span>

</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionTimestamp'>
<a href="/questions/780196-is-this-one-of-those-books-that-is">5 years ago</a>
</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionPermalink'>
<a href="/questions/780196-is-this-one-of-those-books-that-is">See all 9 answers</a>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

</div>
<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/56007684-the-usual"><img alt="" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_100x100-c7bfe730633c9983e27caaa66a8e244a.png" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/56007684-the-usual">The Usual</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">Crikey! <br/>I&apos;m not even going to try to answer the first part of the question because: <br/>1/ It would probably take an entire essay to do the job properly. <a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">Crikey! <br />I'm not even going to try to answer the first part of the question because: <br />1/ It would probably take an entire essay to do the job properly. <br />2/ I don't subscribe to Tolstoy's notions of what constitutes "good" and "bad" art. And<br />3/ I strongly suspect I'm not bright enough to understand what you're driving at. <br />This brings me to part 2. <br />To me, Titus Groan is a delight to read, which is more than I can say for Tolkien. Whilst I would never accuse my fellow readers of ineptitude (reserving that for certain best-selling writers), it is a quite densely written book. and does require a decent vocabulary. Presumably this does put a few people off, as does the claustrophobic atmosphere, and the way that the plot is really just something to hang the (frankly gorgeous and deliciously overwritten) descriptive passages on. <br />It's one of those books that you either love or hate depending on whether you "get it" or not. <a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerFooter'>

<div class='flagAnswer'>
<a class="right flag" rel="nofollow" id="flag_link385247" title="Flag this answer as inappropriate." href="/flagged/new?resource_id=385247&amp;resource_type=CommunityAnswer&amp;return_url=%2Fquestions%2F780196-is-this-one-of-those-books-that-is%2Fanswers%2F385247-crikey-i-m-not-even">flag</a>
</div>
<ul class='communityQAFooter answerFooter'>
</ul>

</div>
</div>

</div>

</div>
