        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1739357632" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8521932837888314168"><u>The Good</u>:<br/>Absolutely wonderful prose, and I’m generally not a fan of the literary stuff. This story is incredibly atmospheric – from the suffocating oppression of the setting to the enormous tragicomic characters. I felt like I was watching rather than reading. Also, there is a multitude of cats.<br/><br/><u>The Bad</u>:<br/>It was a mile high stack of metaphors, like a book overfull of similes. My periods of horrified fascination were separated by too frequent episodes of boredom, as the characters just walked around</span>
  <span id="freeText8521932837888314168" style="display:none"><u>The Good</u>:<br />Absolutely wonderful prose, and I’m generally not a fan of the literary stuff. This story is incredibly atmospheric – from the suffocating oppression of the setting to the enormous tragicomic characters. I felt like I was watching rather than reading. Also, there is a multitude of cats.<br /><br /><u>The Bad</u>:<br />It was a mile high stack of metaphors, like a book overfull of similes. My periods of horrified fascination were separated by too frequent episodes of boredom, as the characters just walked around doing things. The story itself lacked meaning, at least to my lizard brain.<br /><br /><u>'Friends' character the protagonist is most like</u>:<br />There are two protagonists in this work, diametrically opposed. Like Rachel, Steerpike is charming, ambitious and manipulative. Mr Flay is surly like Chandler, and also gets very physical with a chef.</span>
