<div id="review_2049302135" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2049302135" />
    <a title="Greg" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/39346323-greg"><img alt="Greg" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1513962691p2/39346323.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2049302135?book_show_action=true">Jul 04, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Greg" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Greg" href="/user/show/39346323-greg">Greg</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/39346323-greg?shelf=20th-century">20th-century</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/39346323-greg?shelf=oddities">oddities</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/39346323-greg?shelf=reviewed">reviewed</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/39346323-greg?shelf=favorites-of-all-time">favorites-of-all-time</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2049302135" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4012145465016472335">This marks my 1,000th book read as listed on Goodreads! And this landmark should be, and is, something spectacular, awesome, unique, unclassifiable, brilliant, and unequaled. Oddly, I&apos;d never even heard of this author or of any of his books until a few months ago when a goodreads friend brought him to my attention. This trilogy has been compared to &quot;Lord of the Rings&quot; but I don&apos;t know why: this isn&apos;t fantasy, or syfy, or...well, anything. (Besides, it is so much better, so much more imaginative </span>
  <span id="freeText4012145465016472335" style="display:none">This marks my 1,000th book read as listed on Goodreads! And this landmark should be, and is, something spectacular, awesome, unique, unclassifiable, brilliant, and unequaled. Oddly, I'd never even heard of this author or of any of his books until a few months ago when a goodreads friend brought him to my attention. This trilogy has been compared to "Lord of the Rings" but I don't know why: this isn't fantasy, or syfy, or...well, anything. (Besides, it is so much better, so much more imaginative than LOTR.) Perhaps Mary Shelley and Bram Stoker, along with Dickens and Poe, collaborated and channeled it through Peake. In the introduction, Anthony Burgess writes: "It is, if you like, a rich wine of fancy chilled by the intellect to just the right temperature. There is no really close relative to it in all our prose literature. It is uniquely brilliant, and we are right to call it a modern classic." What's it about? Just open it and start reading, go in knowing nothing, and you'll join the ranks of those of us calling this one of the greats of all time. I think I'm going to write a strongly worded letter to my congressperson demanding there be a law that anyone who says they love to read MUST read this book. </span>
  <a data-text-id="4012145465016472335" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


